C++ Solution:
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        int n = digits.size();
        
        // Start from the last digit and move backwards
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            // If the digit is not 9, just add 1 and we are done
            if (digits[i] < 9) {
                digits[i]++;
                return digits;
            }
            
            // If the digit is 9, it becomes 0, and the loop continues 
            // to the next digit to simulate a "carry"
            digits[i] = 0;
        }
        
        // If we exit the loop, it means all digits were 9 (e.g., 999 became 000)
        // We need to add a 1 to the front of the array to make it 1000
        digits.insert(digits.begin(), 1);
        
        return digits;
    }
};

JAVA Solution:
class Solution {
    public int[] plusOne(int[] digits) {
        int n=digits.length;
        for(int i=n - 1;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if(digits[i]<9)
            {
                digits[i]++;
                return digits;
            }
            digits[i]=0;
        }
        int[] newDigits=new int[digits.length+1];
        newDigits[0]=1;
        return newDigits;
    }
}

EXPLAINATION:
The core idea of the code is to work backwards from the end of the array, just like how you do addition by hand, carrying over the "1" only when necessary.

Example 1: digits = [1, 2, 3]
(This applies to Example 2 [4, 3, 2, 1] as well)

In this scenario, we don't have to worry about carrying any numbers over.

The Loop Starts: The for loop starts at the last index (i = 2). The digit here is 3.

The Check: The code asks: if (digits[i] < 9). Since 3 is less than 9, this is true.

The Action: It increments that digit by one (digits[i]++), making it 4. The array is now [1, 2, 4].

The Return: It immediately hits return digits;. The loop stops entirely, and we are done.

It never even looks at the 1 or the 2 because it doesn't need to!

Example 3: digits = [9]
This is the edge case where a "carry" cascades all the way off the front of the array.

The Loop Starts: The for loop starts at the last (and only) index (i = 0). The digit here is 9.

The Check: The code asks: if (digits[i] < 9). Since 9 is not less than 9, this is false. It skips the if block.

The Carry: Because it was a 9, it executes digits[i] = 0;. The array is now [0].

The Loop Ends: Because there are no more digits to check to the left, the for loop finishes.

The Insert: The code moves to the bottom line: digits.insert(digits.begin(), 1);. This forces a 1 into the very front of the array.

The Return: The array is now [1, 0], which is the correct answer, and it returns.

A Hidden "Middle" Example: digits = [1, 9]
LeetCode didn't provide an example where a carry happens in the middle, but here is how the code handles it to solidify your understanding:

Start at the end (i = 1): The digit is 9. It's not less than 9, so it becomes 0. The array is now [1, 0]. The loop moves to the next number to the left.

Move left (i = 0): The digit is 1. The code asks: if (digits[i] < 9). Since 1 is less than 9, this is true!

Finish up: It increments the 1 to a 2. The array is now [2, 0]. It immediately returns, and the insert line at the very bottom is ignored.
